    <fr:p>We will show that we are either in case (a) or case (b) of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml"
number="4.4.8" />, for every place of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex> simultaneously.
      This is clear (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml"
number="4.4.8" />) under the hypothesis (c.1), and follows from <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.10"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.10.xml"
taxon="Lemma"
number="4.4.10" /> under the hypotheses (c.2) or (c.3), since not only <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _T]]></fr:tex>, but also <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _{H\rho }]]></fr:tex>, is then independent of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>Condition (b) of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml"
number="4.4.8" /> cannot be satisfied at every place of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex>, since the Hodge structure would then be locally constant, which (by <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.3"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.1.3.3.xml"
number="4.1.3.3" /> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3.xml"
taxon="Reminder"
number="4.4.3" />) contradicts (b).
      Condition (a) is thus satisfied at each place of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex>, and so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H]]></fr:tex> is of degree <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(0,0)]]></fr:tex> (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.xml"
number="4.4.8" />).
      Taking <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.3.xml"
taxon="Reminder"
number="4.4.3" /> into account, this finishes the proof.</fr:p>
